[1] Cholera - Malawi (Nsanje District)
Date: Sun 1 Mar 2015
Source: Malawi24 [edited]
http://allafrica.com/stories/201503021516.html


International humanitarian organizations have hinted on being alert together with the Malawi government amidst the cholera scare in Malawi's borders. This comes amidst incessant scares of the outbreak in Malawi's borders. UNICEF states on its website that it is on high alert following a cholera outbreak in the southern border areas, where highly populated camps for people displaced by the floods are located.

"Over a period of 2 weeks, the Ministry of Health has confirmed 39 cases of cholera, including 2 deaths. New concerns are that a rapid spread of infection could lead to a larger outbreak that already over-burdened health services may not be able to contain. There are also new alarming reports in neighboring Mozambique (which shares a border with Malawi), which has recorded more than 3400 cholera cases and 37 deaths since 25 Dec 2014, many of them children."

"As humanitarian actors in Malawi, we need to move quickly to stop any further spread of this disease," said UNICEF's representative in Malawi, Mahimbo Mdoe. "These displaced populations are extremely vulnerable, particularly those with low immunity, such as malnourished children. UNICEF is working to support the government with mobile health services, as well as safe water, sanitation and hygiene services, which are critical factors in preventing the spread of cholera."

Cholera poses a serious public health problem to populations in crowded environments, with inadequate water and sanitation resources. While cholera is endemic in Malawi, no cases have been reported in the last 3 years. The last time the country experienced a large-scale outbreak was in 2009, when well over 1000 people were infected.

UNICEF's chief of health in Malawi, Kyaw Aung, says so far UNICEF has begun measures to stop the outbreak from spreading further. "UNICEF has dispatched protective equipment, 30 cholera beds, 15 isolation tents, medicines, IV fluids and 1450 bottles of chlorine in health facilities," said Mr Aung.

The cholera outbreak is [most strongly] feared in Nsanje, which borders Mozambique and was also affected by floods that hit the nation in February 2015.

[byline: Paul Nthala]

